STRUCTURE. Head and thorax somewhat compressed laterally and arched dorsally (
Figs 1–3
). Frontal suture sinuate (
Fig. 2
); antennae bases brought together, frons between them keel-shaped and elevated above clypeus (
Figs 1–3
).

Labium with glossae and paraglossae equally wide, paraglossae slightly longer than glossae; base of glossa very slightly overlap base of paraglossa in ventral view; base of paraglossa somewhat projected laterally (
Figs 30
, 
37
). Ventral side of glossa with numerous irregularly situated long hair-like setae (
Fig. 36
). Dorsal side of glossa with especially stout long setae forming regular transverse row in distal part of glossa and shorter irregular transverse row more distally; middle part of dorsal side with small group of irregularly situated long hair-like setae (
Fig. 37
). Row of long setae along median side of glossa (usual for 
Baetidae
) either regular (
Fig. 37
), or irregular. Paraglossa without setal rows on median and lateral sides; distal margin with numerous long setae (
Fig. 40
) and with 2 somewhat thicker long setae on dorsal side close to apex (
Fig. 39
).

Mesonotum with anterolateral corners projected anteriorly (
Fig. 41
). Fore protoptera brought together, but not fused with posterior margin of mesonotum (
Fig. 42
) (in contrast to 

Pseudopannota

). Lateral margin of fore protopteron with small incision corresponding to costal brace (
Fig. 41
). Metanotum without vestiges of hind protoptera (
Fig. 43
). Thoracic sterna partly sclerotized and pigmented: prosternum with unpaired sclerite, mesosternum and metasternum each with pair of sclerites of peculiar shape (
Fig. 43
). Sclerites of thoracic pleura and sterna partly with scales in operculate sockets (similar to that of abdomen).

Legs with cuticle thick and denticulate (
Figs 48–50
). Femora as characterized above [
Guajirolus
/g1 (8)]; fore femur, besides stout setae on outer side, with such setae also on anterior surface—in distal part and along outer side (
Figs 44, 48
). Tibiae of all legs with patella-tibial suture short, so that on inner side patella occupies only 1/3 of tibia (
Figs 44–45
). Tibia of fore leg with sparse small stout pointed setae on anterior side and few small stout setae on inner side (
Fig. 49
; 
Thomas & al. 2005
: fig. 9). Tibiae of middle and hind legs without stout setae on anterior side, with such setae on posterior and inner sides (
Fig. 50
). Tarsus of all legs with row of stout pointed setae on inner side only. Claws as characterized above [
Guajirolus
/g1 (9)] (
Figs 46–47
).

Abdominal terga and sterna with dense scales in operculate sockets (
Figs 60–61
). Posterior margin of tergum I smooth, without denticles. Posterior margins of terga II–X with row of triangular denticles; denticles of more anterior terga shorter and blunt (
Fig. 62
), denticles of more posterior terga longer and pointed (
Fig. 63
); on middle of posterior margin of tergum IX (behind submedian pair of setae) denticles smaller. Posterior margins of sterna I–VII smooth, without denticles; sternum VIII with blunt denticles on median part of posterior margin (
Fig. 64
); sternum IX with pointed denticles on posterior margin (
Figs 65
, 
76
). Paraprocts with 10–20 pointed denticles, increasing in size toward caudal margin (
Fig. 69
).

Tergalii I absent (
Fig. 43
). Tergalii II–V subequal, tergalii VI–VII gradually diminished (
Figs 51–58
). Each tergalius oval; costal and anal ribs fused apically, so that entire margin armed by costa; in distal half margin with pointed seta-bearing denticles (
Figs 67–68
); dorsal surface with scales in operculate sockets (
Figs 66, 68
).

Paracercus as thick as cerci and somewhat shorter (
Figs 1
, 
52
). Cerci and paracercus with dense primary swimming setae at most their length and with slender distal portion lacking swimming setae. In proximal and distal parts of cercus segments cylindrical, in middle part slightly oblique (
Fig. 59
); posterior margins of segments with regular rows of flat denticles, nearly equally large on dorsal, ventral and lateral sides of cercus (
Fig. 59
), on dorsal and ventral sides of paracercus.

Subimago
.

CUTICULAR COLORATION. Head and pronotum entirely colorless. Prealar bridge contrastingly dark brown (
Fig. 72
). Mesonotum partly colorless, with certain areas shed with light brownish (
Fig. 72
). Pterothoracic pleura and sterna at most part colorless, with certain sclerites contrastingly brown (
Fig. 73
). Legs entirely colorless. Abdomen, genitals and cerci entirely colorless.

HYPODERMAL COLORATION. Just after emergence from larva, most part of body lack hypodermal coloration, being pale ocher; certain areas of thorax brown; abdomen with intersegmental membranes of terga brown, terga with light brownish pigmentation forming paired diffusive maculae (
Fig. 74
). During subimaginal development, thorax and abdominal terga get brown color as in imago.
